<DOC><DOCNO> AP890526-0172 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 2103EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Nigeria-Riots     05-26 0231</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Nigeria-Riots,0240</SECOND><HEAD>Student Protests Continue Despite Military Clampdown, One Death Reported</HEAD><DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Students blocked streets and set tires onfire Friday and a boy was reported killed during a third straightday of clashes between protesters and security forces in amidwestern city.   The protesters are demonstrating against sharp rises in theprice of some basic foods and services, resulting from thegovernment's strict adherence to an austerity program demanded byWestern creditors.   The state-controlled News Agency of Nigeria said an order by themilitary governor to shoot rioters on sight and a dusk-to-dawncurfew failed to quell the disturbances in Benin, 165 miles east ofLagos.   At least 100 people have been reported injured, 15 seriousenough to require hospitalization, Lagos newspapers said. TheUniversity of Benin was ordered closed, the news agency said.   At one stage, rioters stormed Radio Nigeria's local broadcaststation and forced workers to flee, the news agency reported. Thedead youth's body was found in front of the station, it said.   Lagos newspapers said police had avoided confronting the riotersduring the first two days of demonstrations.   The students, joined by some local street traders, market women,taxi drivers and unemployed men, also broke into a local jail andfreed 600 prisoners.   Disturbances were reported earlier in the week in several otheruniversity cities, including Lagos, but they died out quickly.</TEXT></DOC>